//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_enshrine}

NOTE: This operation enshrines upstream base images into
{gar_service}
as content-addressed, human-readable anchors.
The
{rbtr_director}
submits a Cloud Build job that copies each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
from its upstream registry to GAR using
the reliquary skopeo image
(`skopeo copy --all`), preserving the manifest list and all per-platform manifests for multi-platform images.
The locator results are returned via `buildStepOutputs` and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is then written back to the vessel regime locally as a
{rbst_locator}.

NOTE: This operation is a pure mirror.
Every call inspects current upstream for each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
, computes the content-addressed locator from the live manifest digest, copies the image into
{gar_service}
, and writes the resulting
{rbst_locator}
into the vessel's
{rbrv_image_anchor}
— overwriting whatever was previously committed there.
The
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is a derived artifact of this operation, not an operator-set pin.
Re-runs are idempotent with respect to upstream state, not with respect to the file's prior contents — when upstream rotates, the next call writes a different locator and that is the operation surfacing the change, not a fault.

NOTE: Vessels whose
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is written by an upstream procedure as a hallmark-pin (e.g., the airgap-bottle pointing at the just-ordained forge image via `{gar_hallmarks_namespace}/«HALLMARK»/«BASENAME»:«HALLMARK»`) do not invoke this operation.
The orchestrating procedure (handbook step or onboarding-sequence fixture) writes the locator directly;
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
resolves it at build time.
The hallmark's existence in
{gar_service}
is established by the producer's
{rbtgo_ark_ordain}
success, not by a separate validation step here.
